Mutual funds:
1. Mutual Funds (Managed by fund houses, investing in different assets)
A. Equity Mutual Funds (Stock Market-based)
â€¢	Large-Cap Funds â€“  Invest in top large companies (e.g., Nifty 50 stocks). Nifty 50,sensex 30 all are comes under large cap
â€¢	Mid-Cap Funds â€“ Invest in mid-sized companies with high growth potential.
â€¢	Small-Cap Funds â€“ Invest in small, high-risk, high-reward companies.
â€¢	Multi-Cap Funds â€“ Invest across large, mid, and small-cap companies.
â€¢	Flexi-Cap Funds â€“ Similar to multi-cap but fund managers decide allocation freely. Large cap(60%) small cap(20%) midcap(20%) it's equal to Flexi cap
â€¢	Sectoral Funds â€“ Focus on specific sectors (e.g., IT, Pharma, Banking).
â€¢	Thematic Funds â€“ Invest based on themes like ESG (Environmental, Social, Governance).
â€¢	ELSS (Equity Linked Savings Scheme) â€“ Tax-saving equity funds with a 3-year lock-in.
â€¢	Dividend Yield Funds â€“ Focus on companies with high dividend payouts.
â€¢	Contra Funds â€“ Invest in undervalued stocks (contrarian investing).
â€¢	Focused Equity Funds â€“ Invest in a small number of high-conviction stocks.
B. Debt Mutual Funds (Fixed Income-based)
â€¢	Liquid Funds â€“ Invest in short-term, high-liquidity instruments.
â€¢	Ultra Short-Term Funds â€“ Slightly longer than liquid funds but higher returns.
â€¢	Short-Term Debt Funds â€“ Bonds with 1-3 years of maturity.
â€¢	Corporate Bond Funds â€“ Invest in high-rated corporate bonds.
â€¢	Gilt Funds â€“ Invest only in government securities (low risk, moderate returns).
â€¢	Dynamic Bond Funds â€“ Adjust investments based on interest rate changes.
â€¢	Credit Risk Funds â€“ Invest in lower-rated bonds with higher returns.
â€¢	Banking & PSU Debt Funds â€“ Focus on bonds issued by banks & PSUs.
â€¢	Money Market Funds â€“ Invest in ultra-short-term debt instruments.
â€¢	Fixed Maturity Plans (FMPs) â€“ Close-ended debt funds with a fixed maturity.
â€¢	Overnight Funds â€“ Invest in securities that mature in one day.
C. Hybrid Mutual Funds (Mix of equity & debt)
â€¢	Aggressive Hybrid Funds â€“ Higher equity portion (65%-80%), moderate risk.
â€¢	Balanced Hybrid Funds â€“ Equal mix of equity & debt.
â€¢	Conservative Hybrid Funds â€“ Higher debt portion (70%-85%), lower risk.
â€¢	Dynamic Asset Allocation Funds â€“ Adjust investment allocation dynamically.
â€¢	Multi-Asset Allocation Funds â€“ Invest in multiple asset classes (equity, debt, gold).
â€¢	Equity(stocks)+ debt(bond) = hybrid fund
D. Index Funds & ETFs (Passive Investing)
â€¢	Index Funds â€“ Mimic market indices like Nifty 50 or Sensex.
â€¢	Exchange-Traded Funds (ETFs) â€“ Trade like stocks, tracking an index.
â€¢	Sectoral/Thematic ETFs â€“ Follow a specific sector or theme.
