ðŸ“Œ Key Ratios for Mutual Fund Performance Analysis
When analyzing mutual funds, these ratios help determine risk, return, and volatility. Hereâ€™s what each ratio means and the ideal values:
________________________________________
1ï¸âƒ£ Alpha (Î±) â€“ Measures Fund Performance vs. Benchmark
âœ… Definition: Measures how much a fund outperforms or underperforms its benchmark.
âœ… Formula: Alpha = Fund Return - Benchmark Return
Alpha Value	Meaning
Positive (+Î±) âœ…	Good â€“ Fund is performing better than the benchmark.
Zero (0) âš–	Neutral â€“ Fund performs equal to the benchmark.
Negative (-Î±) âŒ	Bad â€“ Fund is underperforming the benchmark.
ðŸ”¹ Ideal Alpha: +2 or higher is considered good.
ðŸ”¹ Example: If a fund has Alpha = 3, it means the fund gave 3% more return than its benchmark.
________________________________________
2ï¸âƒ£ Beta (Î²) â€“ Measures Fund Volatility vs. Market
âœ… Definition: Indicates how much a fund moves relative to the market (benchmark).
âœ… Formula: Beta = Fund Volatility / Market Volatility
Beta Value	Meaning
1.0 âš–	Moves exactly like the market (benchmark).
> 1.0 ðŸ”º	High Risk, High Return â€“ More volatile than the market.
< 1.0 ðŸ”»	Low Risk, Low Return â€“ Less volatile than the market.
ðŸ”¹ Ideal Beta: Between 0.8 and 1.2 is considered stable.
ðŸ”¹ Example: A Beta of 1.2 means the fund is 20% more volatile than the market.
________________________________________
3ï¸âƒ£ Sharpe Ratio â€“ Measures Risk-Adjusted Return
âœ… Definition: Tells how much extra return a fund gives for each unit of risk taken.
âœ… Formula: (Fund Return - Risk-Free Return) / Standard Deviation
Sharpe Ratio	Meaning
> 1.0 âœ…	Good â€“ Higher return for the risk taken.
0.5 - 1.0 âš 	Moderate â€“ Acceptable performance.
< 0.5 âŒ	Poor â€“ Low return for the risk taken.
ðŸ”¹ Ideal Sharpe Ratio: Above 1.0 is best.
ðŸ”¹ Example: If a fund has a Sharpe Ratio of 1.5, it means youâ€™re getting 1.5 units of return per unit of risk.
________________________________________
4ï¸âƒ£ Standard Deviation (SD) â€“ Measures Fund Volatility
âœ… Definition: Tells how much the fundâ€™s returns fluctuate from its average return.
âœ… Higher SD = More Risk, Lower SD = More Stability.
Standard Deviation	Meaning
High (> 20%) âš 	Very volatile fund â€“ Higher risk.
Medium (10-20%) âœ…	Moderate risk â€“ Suitable for most investors.
Low (< 10%) ðŸ”»	Stable fund â€“ Lower risk.
ðŸ”¹ Ideal Standard Deviation: 10-15% for equity funds, 3-5% for debt funds.
ðŸ”¹ Example: If a fund has SD of 18%, its returns fluctuate 18% up or down from its average return.
________________________________________
ðŸ“Š Summary Table â€“ Ideal Ratios for a Good Fund
Ratio	What It Measures	Good Value
Alpha (Î±)	Performance vs. Benchmark	+2 or more
Beta (Î²)	Volatility vs. Market	0.8 â€“ 1.2
Sharpe Ratio	Risk-Adjusted Returns	> 1.0
Standard Deviation	Volatility of Returns	10-15% for equity funds
________________________________________
ðŸ” How to Use These Ratios for Investment?
âœ… If Alpha is positive & Sharpe Ratio > 1, the fund is performing well.
âœ… If Beta is around 1, the fund is stable (not too risky).
âœ… If Standard Deviation is low, the fund is less volatile.
âœ… Compare these ratios across funds in the same category before investing.
